Amadou Diallo, an unarmed street vendor from Guinea, was tragically shot 19 times by white police officers in his own building.
The incident sparked protests against police brutality and racial profiling.
The officers, charged with murder, face trial amid public outcry.
Diallo's parents seek justice for their son's senseless killing.
The defense claims the shooting was a tragic mistake, not a crime.
Forensic evidence will play a crucial role in the trial, as conflicting interpretations emerge.
The legal process unfolds as the officers return to work pending trial, setting the stage for a contentious legal battle.
